🔐 3️⃣ Security Knowledge Required

Now the important part.

You must understand how attacks work BEFORE automating them.

Study these topics deeply:

🔥 Authentication Attacks

Learn how these work manually:

Brute force

Session fixation

Session reuse

JWT tampering

Missing authentication

Method bypass

🔥 Authorization Attacks

Understand:

IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference)

Vertical privilege escalation

Horizontal privilege escalation

Forced browsing

Multi-tenant isolation failure

Practice manually using:

OWASP Juice Shop

DVWA

Manual understanding → then automate.

⚙️ 4️⃣ Scanner Engineering Concepts

This is what makes your project professional.

You must understand:

✅ Differential Analysis

Compare:

Authenticated response

Unauthenticated response

Check:

Status code

Response length

Content similarity

✅ State Management

Your tool must handle:

Logged-in state

Logged-out state

Multiple users

Multiple tokens

✅ Automation Logic

Understand:

If X happens → report vulnerability.

Example logic thinking:

If unauthenticated request returns 200 OK
AND response looks like protected data
→ Missing authentication
📚 Learning Order (Very Important)

Follow this order:

🥇 Phase 1 (1–2 weeks)

HTTP fundamentals

How cookies work

How sessions work

Basic Python requests

JSON parsing

🥈 Phase 2 (1–2 weeks)

Manual testing of auth flaws

Practice IDOR

Practice method bypass

Practice missing authentication

Understand attacks deeply.

🥉 Phase 3 (Start Coding)

Only after you fully understand:

How to detect manually

What signals indicate vulnerability

Then begin coding scanner.

🎓 What You Should Be Comfortable Explaining

Before coding, you should be able to explain:

What is the difference between authentication and authorization?

How does session-based login work internally?

What is JWT structure?

How does IDOR happen?

Why does HTTP method bypass work?

How do scanners detect vulnerabilities automatically?

If you cannot explain these clearly → learn more first.

